The Core Problem
Imagine a busy airport. If every pilot had to talk directly to every other pilot in the sky to figure out who is landing next, 
it would be a disaster. In software, we call this "spaghetti code"—when UI components (like a button, a checkbox, and a text field) 
or microservices all hold direct references to each other and call each other's methods.

When everything is tightly coupled like this, changing one class forces you to change several others,
and reusing a class in a different part of the app becomes impossible.

The Solution: The Air Traffic Controller
The Mediator pattern solves this by introducing an Air Traffic Control (ATC) tower.
The planes (your objects) do not talk to each other. They only talk to the ATC tower (the Mediator). 
The tower knows the status of all planes and routes the messages accordingly.

The Three Pillars (Structure)
The Mediator: An interface that declares the communication methods (usually just a notify() or send() method).

The Concrete Mediator: The actual "hub" (the ATC tower). It holds references to all the components and contains the routing logic.

The Components (Colleagues): The independent objects (the planes). They only have a reference to the Mediator interface. 
They don't know the concrete classes of the other components.
